x0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNow that nearly twenty years have passed since the collapse of the Soviet bloc there is a need to understand what has taken place since that historic date and where we are at the moment. Bringing together authors with different historical, cultural, regional and theoretical backgrounds, this volume engages in debates that address new questions arising from recent developments, such as whether there is a need to reject or uphold the notion of post-socialism as both a necessary and valid concept ignoring changes and differences across both time and space. The authors’ firsthand ethnographies from their own countries belie such a simplistic notion, revealing, as they do, the cultural, social, and historical diversity of countries of Central and Southeastern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aPolitical anthropologyzEurope, Eastern. 0aPolitical anthropologyzFormer communist countries. 0aPost-communismzEurope, Eastern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBitušíková, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchowski, Michał, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiordano, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoštialová, Katarína, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKubica, Grażyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKürti, László, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKürti, László, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMuršič, Rajko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagy, Terézia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca